Characters: Mollymauk Tealeaf, Caleb Widogast
Additional Tags: POV Second Person, Character Study, Grief/Mourning, Declarations Of Love, Angst, Hurt/Comfort, Bittersweet Ending, Closure, Canonical Character Death, Nonbinary Mollymauk Tealeaf
Summary:

“Something weighing on your mind, hm?”

Something like bone paste cakes your tongue; thick as frosting but bitter, so bitter. “You’re dead.”

They shrug. “Happens. A shame, though, I was so hoping to celebrate when we returned home.”

“We do not have a home.”

“We were making one.”

summary: Yeza telling the M9 a lot about Nott/Veth and she's just embarrassed of all the things her husband is saying
question: Yeza telling the M9 a lot about Nott/Veth and she's just embarrassed of all the things her husband is saying
answer:
+ Anon: The M9 asking Yeza how is Nott/Veth as a wife and Yeza just all blush out every time he talks about her

They’ve just crossed the border back into the Empire, and Yeza is looking less and less shellshocked by the day, when Beau asks. She knows it’s a touchy subject, but she’s curious. “Hey, Yeza. What was Nott like when you guys lived in Felderwin?” He startles when she addresses him, but it quickly morphs  into a thoughtful look.

    “Well, my wife is the kindest person you’ll ever meet. You know, back when we were first married, she’d bring home strays all the time. Birds with broken wings, stray cats, even a baby raccoon, once!” by now, the whole group has gathered around to hear him talk, and they smirk at the similarities to Nott and Caleb’s situation, “Oh, and she’s so smart, too. Smarter than me, though she always denies it. You know, when I first showed her how to make dyes, she picked it up right away? It took me a week to learn what she picked up in just a couple hours!” Caleb nods as he says this. He’s glad he’s not the only one who knows how smart she is,

    “Not to mention she’s the most beautiful woman I’ve ever met. Her freckles remind me of the stars, you know. Sometimes, when we’d stargaze I’d tell her that the stars have nothing on her. And her hands, oh, her hands. I’d sometimes get distracted, staring at them. They’re rough, you can tell how hard she works from all the scars, and covered in tiny freckles, too.”

    Nott sits in the corner of the camp, getting greener and greener as Yeza speaks. She knows that Yeza has always seen the best in her, even when she didn’t see it herself. You’d think she’d hung the moon, listening to him go on! As he speaks, she stares at her hands. They’re a deep forest green, mottled through with other, lighter shades. They’re even rougher than what they were when she was a halfling, thanks to a mixture of her tougher goblin skin and the efforts of loading a hand crossbow all the time. Still covered in freckles, though they’re a light green instead of the dark brown they used to be.

    She looks up to see Yeza has wandered over. The group has dispersed, lingering suspiciously long on the other side of the camp. “Do you- um, do you really still think all of that?” she asks quietly, the words barely audible. Yeza cups her face in his hands. “Vethy, I thought you’d died. You did die. For a year, I wished I could bring you back, even for just a second. To actually have you back? It’s a dream come true! I love you, Veth, no matter if you’ve got claws or not,” both of their eyes are shining when he finishes. Slowly, making sure that she can move away if she wants, Yeza leans forward to kiss her. She wraps her arms gently around his neck, before gently pulling away. “I’ve missed you so much, Yeza,” she whispers.

“I’m so glad to have you back, Veth.”

Yeza cups her face in his hands. “Vethy, I thought you’d died. You did die. For a year, I wished I could bring you back, even for just a second. To actually have you back? It’s a dream come true!
